BEGIN_PGML
A chef had [`\frac{2}{3}`] cups of flour and needed to use [`\frac{1}{8}`] cup to thicken a sauce. How much flour is left? [_]{$ev}{15}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
We need to compute [`\frac{2}{3} - \frac{1}{8}\text{.}`] The denominators are [`3`] and [`8\text{.}`] One common denominator is [`24\text{,}`] so we move to rewrite each fraction using [`24`] as the denominator:

[```\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
\frac{2}{3} - \frac{1}{8}\amp=\frac{2\cdot8}{3\cdot8} - \frac{1\cdot3}{8\cdot3}\\
\amp=\frac{16}{24}-\frac{3}{24}\\
\amp=\frac{13}{24}
\end{aligned}
```]

The numerical result is [`\frac{13}{24}\text{,}`] but a pure number does not answer this question. The amount of flour remaining is [`\frac{13}{24}`] _cups_.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

